\begin_layout Section
The two-level atom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-level atom is a simple model system that can be used to explore the interactions produced by electromagnetic waves. As before, we can use a perturbative approach to explore this system. The Hamiltonian of the atom, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_0$
\end_inset

, admits two energy eigenstates, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_2$
\end_inset

, with corresponding energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_2$
\end_inset

. If required, we will assume 
\begin_inset Formula $E_1 < E_2$
\end_inset

. In Dirac notation, we can label these states 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert 1 \rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert 2 \rangle$
\end_inset

. The energies of these states differ by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E = \hbar\Delta\omega$
\end_inset

. The perturbation Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_I$
\end_inset

 originates from the electric dipole operator, which is the position operator scaled by the charge: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d} = q\hat{x}$
\end_inset

. The energy of a dipole is given by the dot product 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{d} \cdot \vec{E}$
\end_inset

. The electric field generated by an electromagnetic wave can be expressed in terms of a cosine function scaled by the magnitude of the oscillation and the direction of polarization: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{H} = \hat{H}_0 - \hat{d} \cdot \vec{\varepsilon} E_0 \cos \omega t
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen already, the evolution of a wavefunction of the two-level atom perturbed by an electromagnetic wave can be expressed in terms of time-dependent coefficients that contribute to the expected time evolution of each eigenstate: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi\left(\vec{x},t\right) = 
    c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_1 t} \phi_1 +
    c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_2 t} \phi_2
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the previous derivation for the time evolution of the coefficients, we can find expressions for the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_1\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{1}{i\hbar}\sum_{n = 1}^{2} c_n\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_n - E_1\right) t}
    \langle \phi_1 \vert -\hat{d} \cdot \vec{\varepsilon} E_0 \cos \omega t \vert \phi_n \rangle
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{1}{i\hbar} \sum_{n = 1}^{2} c_n\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_n - E_2\right) t}
    \langle \phi_2 \vert -\hat{d} \cdot \vec{\varepsilon} E_0 \cos \omega t \vert \phi_n \rangle
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

To shorten this expression, we define the 
\shape italic
dipole matrix
\shape default
, a matrix representation of the dipole operator in terms of our eigenbasis and the electric field. The dot product with the polarization vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 may be pulled out of the expression. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
d^{\varepsilon}_{ab}
& =
\langle \phi_a \vert -\hat{d} \cdot \vec{\varepsilon} \, \vert \phi_b \rangle
\\
& = -\vec{\varepsilon} \cdot \langle \phi_a \vert \hat{d} \vert \phi_b \rangle
\\
& = -q \vec{\varepsilon} \cdot \langle \phi_a \vert \hat{x} \vert \phi_b \rangle
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

Because the position operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian, the dipole moment operator is also Hermitian, corresponding to the fact that the dipole moment is an observable quantity. This also means that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{\varepsilon}_{ab} = d^{\varepsilon *}_{ba}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can rephrase our equation in terms of a matrix and vector in the eigenbasis given by the unperturbed Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_0$
\end_inset

. This allows us to write the unperturbed Hamiltonian as a diagonal matrix with the entries being the energies of each state. The SchrÃ¶dinger equation then looks like: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
i\hbar\partialderivative{t} 
\begin{bmatrix}
    c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_1 t} \\
    c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_2 t}
\end{bmatrix}
=
\left(
\begin{bmatrix} E_1 & 0 \\ 0 & E_2 \end{bmatrix} + E_0 \cos \left(\omega t\right)
\begin{bmatrix}
    d^{\varepsilon}_{11} & d^{\varepsilon}_{12} \\
    d^{\varepsilon}_{21} & d^{\varepsilon}_{22}
\end{bmatrix}
\right) 
\begin{bmatrix}
    c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_1 t} \\
    c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_2 t}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

However, we can absorb the diagonal components of the perturbation matrix into the energies of the eigenstates, making the substitutions 
\begin_inset Formula $E_1 \to E_1 + d^{\varepsilon}_{11}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_2 \to E_2 + d^{\varepsilon}_{22}$
\end_inset

. We can then define 
\begin_inset Formula $D = d^{\varepsilon}_{12}$
\end_inset

, and use the Hermitian property to simplify even further: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
i\hbar\partialderivative{t} 
\begin{bmatrix}
    c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_1 t} \\
    c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_2 t}
\end{bmatrix}
=
\left(
\begin{bmatrix} E_1 & 0 \\ 0 & E_2 \end{bmatrix} + E_0 \cos \left(\omega t\right)
\begin{bmatrix} 0 & D \\ D^* & 0 \end{bmatrix}
\right) 
\begin{bmatrix}
    c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_1 t} \\
    c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E_2 t}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

We can substitute this simplification back into our original equations, exploiting the fact that our perturbation is zero along the diagonal. This means that the time evolution of one coefficient depends only on the other coefficient: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{1}{i\hbar} c_2\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_2 - E_1\right) t}
    E_0 \cos \left(\omega t\right) D
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{1}{i\hbar} c_1\left(t\right) e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(E_1 - E_2\right) t}
    E_0 \cos \left(\omega t\right) D^*
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

We can perform one more simplification with the identification of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E = E_2 - E_1$
\end_inset

 and using a frequency representation instead, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \omega$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{D^* E_0 }{i\hbar} \cos \left(\omega t\right) e^{-i \Delta \omega t} c_2\left(t\right)
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
\frac{D E_0}{i\hbar}    \cos \left(\omega t\right) e^{i \Delta \omega t} c_1\left(t\right)
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

If we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is real, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{D E_0}{\hbar}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\shape italic
Rabi frequency
\shape default
, which we represent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_0$
\end_inset

. We can also describe the cosines in terms of imaginary exponentials: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
-i\Omega_0 \frac{e^{i\omega t} + e^{-i\omega t}}{2} e^{-i \Delta \omega t} c_2\left(t\right)
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
-i\Omega_0 \frac{e^{i\omega t} + e^{-i\omega t}}{2} e^{i \Delta \omega t} c_1\left(t\right)
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

By combining the exponential terms, we get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
-\frac{i\Omega_0}{2} 
\left(
    e^{i\left(\omega - \Delta \omega\right) t} + 
    e^{-i\left(\omega + \Delta \omega\right) t}\right)
c_2\left(t\right)
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
-\frac{i\Omega_0}{2} 
\left(
    e^{-i\left(\omega - \Delta \omega\right) t} + 
    e^{i\left(\omega + \Delta \omega\right) t}\right)
c_1\left(t\right)
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega - \Delta \omega$
\end_inset

 is the detuning that we identified earlier. the detuning parameter corresponds to a slow oscillation, but the other parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega + \Delta \omega$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a very fast oscillation that can be averaged out. Therefore, we can neglect the exponential term that contains the sum of frequencies when our detuning parameter is small: this is the 
\shape italic
rotating wave approximation
\shape default
. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{flalign}
\partialderivative{t} c_1\left(t\right)
& =
-\frac{i\Omega_0}{2} e^{i\left(\omega - \Delta \omega\right) t} c_2\left(t\right)
\\
\partialderivative{t} c_2\left(t\right)
& =
-\frac{i\Omega_0}{2} e^{-i\left(\omega - \Delta \omega\right) t}c_1\left(t\right)
\end{flalign}
\end_inset

If the detuning parameter is large, we cannot ignore this parameter, so the approximation becomes invalid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bloch sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavefunction of a two-level atom can be written in terms of its eigenstates: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi\left(\vec{x},t\right) =
    c_1 \phi_1\left(\vec{x},t\right) + c_2 \phi_2\left(\vec{x},t\right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Because we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 are complex, this gives our system four degrees of freedom – at least, to start. However, we know that wavefunctions are identical up to multiplication by a complex constant, which removes two degrees of freedom from the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would be convenient to come up with alternate description of the state space of the two-level atom that did not include the redundancies associated with complex coefficients. We can come up with such a formulation by expressing the normalization condition for the wavefunction: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int \left(c_1 \phi_1\left(\vec{x},t\right) + c_2 \phi_2\left(\vec{x},t\right)\right)^\dagger
    \left(c_1 \phi_1\left(\vec{x},t\right) + c_2 \phi_2\left(\vec{x},t\right)\right) d \vec{x}
    = 1
\end{equation}
\end_inset

We know that the eigenstates form an orthonormal basis, so we can simplify this drastically: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
c_1^\dagger c_1 + c_2^\dagger c_2 = 1
\end{equation}
\end_inset

To split this into two factors, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $c_1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 in terms of two angular parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

, which satisfy the relation: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\cos\theta\right)^2 + e^{-i\varphi} e^{i\varphi} \left(\sin\theta\right)^2  = 1
\end{equation}
\end_inset

and thus gives us a new expression for the wavefunction involving only two real parameters: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi = \phi_1 \cos\theta + \phi_2 e^{i\varphi} \sin\theta
\end{equation}
\end_inset

There is a convenient geometric interpretation of the angular parameters: they represent coordinates on the surface of a sphere. This representation is the 
\shape italic
Bloch sphere
\shape default
. Its surface represents all possible pure states of the system. Mixed states, which will come up later, correspond to points in the interior of the sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The density operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a two-level atom that has been prepared in some state 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(\vec{x},0\right)$
\end_inset

. We know it was prepared in one of two states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_1\left(\vec{x},0\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_2\left(\vec{x},0\right)$
\end_inset

, with equal probability. How can we describe this state? Our first instinct may be to describe the state as a superposition of the two states: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\phi_1 + \phi_2\right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

But this raises a problem: this tells us that the system was prepared in exactly the superposition of states, not in a probabilistic mixture of the two pure states. An experimentalist will not know with certainty that a system is prepared in exactly in one state over the other, but superpositions do not convey this ideay. The uncertainty in state preparation requires its own treatment separate from the quantum mechanical probability amplitudes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to this problem is to define the density operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}$
\end_inset

. Our knowledge of the state of the system can be described by this operator instead of a wavefunction. However, we use wavefunctions to construct the operator. In the system we want to model, we know that the system is certainly in either 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_2$
\end_inset

, but certainly not in any superposition state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\shape italic
pure state
\shape default
 is a state that can be represented as the product of a state vector with itself. For instance, if we managed to generate exactly the state 
\begin_inset Formula $c_1\phi_1 + c_2\phi_2$
\end_inset

, we could describe it in terms of the eigenbasis: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\rho}_{ab} =
\begin{bmatrix}
    c_1^* c_1   &   c_1^* c_2   \\
    c_2^* c_1   &   c_2^* c_2   
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

